I do not have access to the specific scripts or applications you are referring to, but I can provide an example of how to execute a javascript code as a string variable using node.js. Here's a sample code that uses "console.log" to log the value of a "internal token" property on the object "INTERNAL_TOKEN":

```javascript
const program = require('commander');
program
  .name('my-app')
  .version('0.0.1')
  .description('my app description');

program
  .command('login')
    .option('--token', 'provide your custom token here')
    .action((args, options) => {
      const loginOptions = JSON.parse(process.env.INTERNAL_TOKEN); // get the internal token from env variable or default value
      console.log(`Internal token: ${loginOptions.token}`);
    });

program.parse(process.argv); // execute the program with your custom options and arguments
```

assuming that "INTERNAL_TOKEN" is set to a custom value in the environment variables, you can run the above script from your terminal using node.js. The "console.log" command will display the value of the "token" property on the object "INTERNAL_TOKEN".
